-- Sub-Saharan African Equities Report: Cadbury Nigeria, Equity Bank of Kenya
-- Vincent Nwanma
-- 2010-04-26T16:19:19Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-26/sub-saharan-african-equities-report-cadbury-nigeria-equity-bank-of-kenya.html

          
          
             Kenya’s All-Share Index advanced
for a fourth day, climbing 0.6 percent to 71.32 at the close in
Nairobi, an 18-month high.  
 Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rose for a fifth day, advancing
0.2 percent to 1,689.60 at the close in the capital, Port Louis.  
 The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index declined the
most this month, falling 1.6 percent to 26,952.10 at the close
in Lagos, an exchange official who didn’t want to be named said
by phone.  
 The Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index retreated for the
first day in five, falling 0.1 percent to 6,441 at the close in
Accra.  
 Namibia’s FTSE/Namibia Overall Index surged the most in
seven trading days, rising 1.9 percent to 830.65 in the capital,
Windhoek.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Cadbury Nigeria Plc (CADBURY NL) declined 1.19 naira, or
the maximum daily limit of 5 percent, to 22.64 naira, the most
in five weeks. The chocolate maker reported a loss for the year
through December on April 23. The loss narrowed to 1.24 billion
naira ($8.24 million) from 2.74 billion naira a year earlier.  
 Equity Bank Ltd. (EQBNK KN), a Kenyan lender, rose to the
highest level in 15 months, increasing 45 cents, or 2.5 percent,
to 18.85 shillings. The bank reported a 36 percent increase in
first-quarter profit on April 23.  
